〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 ſignifies one that is empty, or drawn dry. Exhauſtus, opibus attenuatus Druſius. It is a Metaphor taken from Ponds, or Rivers that are drawn dry. So, the poor are exhauſted of their ſtrength, beauty, ſubſtance; like Ponds they are dried up, therefore they muſt be filled again with the ſilver ſtreames of Charity;

2. A tender Commiſeration. Iſa. 58. 10. If thou draw out thy ſoul to the hungry; bounty begins in
pity. Quis ignoret ex ea appellatione eſſe miſerecordiam quod miſerum cor faciat condolentis alieno malo. Aug. Tom. 1. lib. 1. The Hebrew word for mercy, 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 ſignifies bowels; Chriſt firſt had compaſſion on the multitude, then he wrought a miracle to feed them, Mat. 15. 32. Charity which wants compaſſion is bruitiſh. The bruit Creatures can releeve us many wayes, but cannot pity us. 'Tis a kind of Cruelty (ſaith Quintilian) to feed one in want, and not to ſympathize with him. True Religion begets tenderneſſe;
〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 Greg. Nazianz. as it melts the heart in tears of contrition towards God, ſo in bowels of compaſsion towards others. Iſa. 11. 16. My bowels ſhall ſound as an harp. Let me allude, when your bowels of pity ſound, then your Almes make ſweet Muſick in the eares of God.
